"4Title: Alcohol by ArcticIllusion at All poetry
"
"	<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"ÆMy name is Samara Rayne. I was born in Brooklyn, New York. I've been a hopeless drug addict and alcoholic for quite some time now. My mother died before I could generate lasting memories and my dad just didn't care. He was exactly like his dad was, an alcoholic, and I think that's been passed down through the generations to me. As far back as I can remember, there was something inherently wrong with the way I felt about myself. I was a really awkward kid, I used movies, played make-believe, had an imaginary friend to get away. I know that sounds like normal stuff for kids to do but it was why I used those things that makes me look back now and realize that all I wanted was an escape from reality.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"³My sister used to watch MTV a lot when I was younger. I started paying attention to it right around the time Nirvana was played about 100 times a day. There was something so </p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"xattractive about the way they were singing and playing that instantly, I realized I had found the escape I had been looking for in music. I was about 10 when I got my first Walkman and every week I would use money I earned to buy more tapes. Grunge was pretty huge then, so I had Nirvana, Alice in Chains, Pearl Jam and Joy Division and my some old Beatles tapes I found.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
" I couldn't get enough.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"êI went into 6th grade the next month and all I wanted was to be in a band. Fuck math, fuck gym, fuck history; fuck everything except for music and fuck everyone except those who played it. I met this kid who was into music I had never heard before. He said it was called punk: Misfits, Green Day, Offspring, Sex Pistols, Bad Religion.it was like I was falling in love all over again. That was &quot;The year that punk broke&quot;. Which is also the year I discovered alcohol and drugs.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"The first time I got drunk was in a park with my friend and his brother. I drank half a 40 of Bull Ice, I was so drunk I couldn't even walk home, they had to carry me. They left me on my front lawn, where at 5:30am my dad found me lying in a pool of my own vomit. I swore to him that I was just sick and needed to go to bed. I'm pretty sure he knew what happened and thought I learned my lesson.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"rAs I said before, I had always felt like there wasn't something quite right inside me, but when I took a drink I felt normal for the first time. I never wanted to feel the way I felt when I was sober again. so I started drinking everyday. My friends and I would ditch school, go steal some beer and drink it at the park. We thought nothing could stop us. We were indestructible. The same friend that got me into punk also introduced me to weed, and we smoked it constantly. By the end of 6th grade I was so excited about this new life that everything else fell by the wayside, then I was kicked out of school that spring.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"4At the start of 7th grade I was back at the same school, doing the same shit: skipping, stealing, telling teachers and principle to go fuck themselves. One month led into the school year and they expelled me from the district for good. Which was fine by me gave me more time to write songs and do drugs.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"óAt this point getting high and music has taken over my life completely. One of my best friends at the time had decided she had enough and one afternoon she wrote a note, took her dad's 9mm and shot herself. Had I not done drugs I wouldn't have made it through that. On my 14th birthday I was a full on heroin, coke and speed junkie. I snorted anything anyone had; will it break down with water or heat? Yeah I did that to. Anything to keep me in away from reality. My friends and I got into crime to support our growing habits, stealing cars, shoplifting tools and returning them for cash, robbing houses, robbing people. Nothing was sacred any more; we had to do everything we could to feed our addictions. I overdosed a number of times, watched friends overdose and die right in front of me, but I couldn't help them because I was too fucked up. I was living on the street, in abandoned houses, or with friends. I had several run-ins with cops and went to jail more times then I can remember. Still even through all of this, the jail time, the treatment centers, losing people I loved, not having a place to go. There was always something constant in my life and it was music. It was always there the pick me up or make me feel that I wasn't alone in all this.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"ÏI've been fighting these addictions now my entire life, and just recently I have been able to stay sober for longer then a month. So far I have been sober for over 3 months and it’s far from being easy.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"Getting clean is different for everyone I guess, for me it took a huge loss of heartache. I had to be a bottom of the barrel junkie. I had to lose everything to wake up; the one constant through the dark and this light was music. It has never let me down.</p>
"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>
"I'll admit it; I'm fucking scared to death of who I was and who I become if I drink. I'm scared all the time because it’s just one fuck up away. One choice and everything I've worked on for the past many months will be gone. But I'm optimistic about the future, I'm excited about what's happening in my life and my band, my friends and my family. I can't wait to see what's around the corner.</p>
"End of Poem
