"-Title: End by Cadee Blaze at All poetry
"
"¥	I sat at the computer, looking down at my phone. &nbsp;I had a message, from whom? &nbsp;It was 9:30 in the morning and I knew that people were still asleep.<br />
"<br />
"ìI reached for it, punching in the numbers, “1-2-3”. &nbsp;Soon my voice mail came on the line. &nbsp;Kris called twice that night. &nbsp;He called around four in the morning and at five. &nbsp;He called to tell me goodbye. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"êI listened to the message, my ear glued to the phone. &nbsp;The rest of the world did not matter to me. &nbsp;Nothing registered but the fact that he was taking his life and he was leaving me. &nbsp;He was leaving me all alone.<br />
"<br />
""Kris put back the pieces of my heart and helped heal my soul. &nbsp;Now, in the blink of an eye, he tore my world in two. &nbsp;I died a little bit that day. &nbsp;A part of me was ripped from my soul, from my heart. &nbsp;The void he filled was once again open but deeper this time.<br />
"<br />
"}I sat the phone down gently on the desk, my other hand covering my mouth. &nbsp;Tears fell from my eyes as water falls down a waterfall. &nbsp;They streamed down my face fast and heavy, not stopping. &nbsp;I had to gain my composure. &nbsp;I could not let my mother see. &nbsp;I had to hide my tears, my pain. &nbsp;I did not want my mother mocking him even in death. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"¥My chest hurt so bad, I thought I was going to faint or die myself. &nbsp;I listened to the message again. &nbsp;I thought, hoped that maybe I was wrong. &nbsp;That I heard it all, imagined it. &nbsp;But alas, it did happen, I did hear it. &nbsp;I stumbled to the bathroom across the hall; my family did not even see me leave my room. &nbsp;Too wrapped up in their own lives, they never even notice my pain. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"ªHe mentioned that it might not work, that he might not die. &nbsp;I clung to that hope, even if it were false hope. &nbsp;It was the only thing keeping me from collapsing. &nbsp;I wanted to call his house, to ask his family. &nbsp;I knew they would not call me back his parents hated me. &nbsp;His mother hated me and blamed me for his problems. &nbsp;I was scared for it to be true; I never picked up the phone. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"ÅI would die for him, yet he could not live for me. &nbsp;Somewhere in my heart I know he is gone. &nbsp;He attempted to kill himself in October; I just prolonged the effect. &nbsp;I knew things were not going well, I knew. &nbsp;I knew he was hurting and I did nothing. &nbsp;Just words came from my mouth over the phone or were typed onto the computer. &nbsp;What if I stayed on the phone longer? &nbsp;So many questions race through my mind as to what I could have done. &nbsp;I should have been able to save him. &nbsp;What if I left my phone on, then I would have heard the ring and wake up. &nbsp;If not to talk him out of committing suicide, at least…at least to say, “Goodbye. &nbsp;I love you.”<br />
"<br />
"%I listen to the messages again; possibly there was something in the message, telling me he was not dead. &nbsp;Nothing, but later I found his goodbye poem. &nbsp;I did not even get to tell him goodbye, one last time. &nbsp;No more “I love you’s” or battle of who loves each other more. <br />
"<br />
"6I will never get to touch him, to love him, to kiss him. &nbsp;He is gone. &nbsp;I know I have to move on. &nbsp;But how can I? &nbsp;My heart is shattered in a million pieces; my soul is lost and alone. &nbsp;I am so confused. &nbsp;My pain ripples through me, as my pool of sorrow grows deeper. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"‰This is another memory to add to my pile locked away in the dark corners of my mind. &nbsp;I have a feeling that this one will haunt me; escape the cage that keeps it hidden. &nbsp;I cry when I remember, now I cry when I remember him. &nbsp;Tears fall from my eyes when I dream of him, think of him. &nbsp;Tears run down my face a few times a day, my eyes-only reflecting sorrow. &nbsp;<br />
"<br />
"ò“Everyone I love leaves me. &nbsp;Will I always be alone?” I mumble to myself, in between gasps and sobs. &nbsp;I lay my head back down on the drenched pillow. &nbsp;Now I have to hide again, put on my mask each morning and slowly die.<br />
"End of Poem
