"ETitle: We are the Masquerade by IronyIsADeadScene at All poetry
"
"Ð		I could hardly see through the small holes in the mask. It was hot and I was sweating from all the dancing. She whirled and twirled around me. Our steps were perfect with the music. She had never looked so beautiful. She was the sparkle dancing on the ocean waves, rising and falling with the moonlight. I was below the water and all they could see what the surface. She was too perfect. They would never look past her. Diamond, they called to her. Her name could not live up to her; her delicate feet, her elegant vanity. She was a picture that framed my heart. <p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mozart was a genius, and he led me strait to her. Each note enticing her to step towards me. I was sure our worlds were about to collide. I braced myself for the impact, and embraced her for the control. It was so much better when she could not get away. It was right when I was the one who chose our fate. The music would have its way.<p>&nbsp;</p></p><p>The beats steadied themselves and I let her step around me. The clicking over her heals on the marble floor. The chandeliers all rivaled her, but could not compete. The rooms shone brighter in her presence than any time before.<p>&nbsp;</p></p><p>I could feel the fear mounting as the music faded. The crowd was closing in and she would be consumed. They were the mouth of the world’s desires. They would engulf her and steal her passion. So we fled. The starry night held us and the darkness stole us away. The rose in her hair was dying and the farther we became from the music the more she went with it. I held her tightly, thinking I could keep the life in her if I held her close enough. The sequins on her breathe were laced with resentment, and the crystals in her eyes were hiding. <p>&nbsp;</p></p><p>She gazed into my eyes and for a moment I was sure I would fall to pieces right in front of her. She raised her arm and gently stroked my cheek. I suspected foul play. And in an instant I regretted our dance. I could breathe again, but I hated her for it. My mask lay at my feet. I tore myself from her bitter embrace and fell to my knees in shame. I listened to her footsteps fade into the dark. <p>&nbsp;</p></p><p>She discovered me, the only thing that would take her from me. I was the only thing that could drive her away. We were that dance. We were the moment under the stars. We were the shock of discovery. We were the shallow footsteps on the cobblestones. We were untouchable and unlovable all together. We were the masquerade. &nbsp;<p>&nbsp;</p></p><p>
"</p>End of Poem
