"?Title: She Wasn't Okay by IronyIsADeadScene at All poetry
"
"Æ	It was stormy outside. Leeann was sprawled out on the floor of her room. Music pounded through her headphones. She didn't dare turn on her stereo; she didn't want to draw attention to herself. &nbsp;Locks of pale blonde hair were entwined in her fingers where she had torn it from her head when she was screaming. She hated screaming, but they had made her do it. They told her that she would feel better, they promised. Of course, they had lied.<br />
" <br />
""The rain poured down onto the window, and trickled down into the rain gutter. She had been listening to the same song for hours, locked away in hiding. Wasn't anyone missing her? The song assured her that she was forgotten. The one thing she had always feared. She could hear the yelling over the throbbing music. Turning the knob up a bit more she lost herself in the melodic singing, the voices just got louder and louder. Subconsciously she pleaded with them. They continued to remind her that she was never going to amount to anything.<br />
"<br />
"The pitch black was consuming her and she almost felt like she couldn’t breathe. The clock read 3:00 a.m. she couldn’t fall asleep, they wouldn’t let her. Insomnia was her only friend tonight. &nbsp;She hummed along to the music. Finally they rested for the night. She smiled and said goodnight. Perhaps, she would get to sleep tonight. They were rather tenacious and only slept on occasion. She had gone for five nights without sleep. She looked up at her bed and sighed. She hadn’t even sat there since the day they joined her. She thought they were just a phase from when she lost him. People didn’t talk to her much after the accident. She has always just thought that since no one would talk to her she had created them to keep her company. She knew that they didn’t love her and that it was their greatest pleasure to hear her scream. She didn’t mind though because at least they knew she was alive. Her friends and parents assumed she had killed him. They didn’t know her at all though. They didn’t know that she had loved him. She hated that she always thought about that day. She couldn’t blame them for thinking that she did it though. When she was found, she was holding him tight, pistol on the floor. Her hands, her face and her clothes were soaked in his blood. <br />
"<br />
"0They awoke the moment they knew she was thinking about him. Screaming at her, they told her that she was a failure. You could have done something; they said a sing-song voice. If you really loved him you wouldn’t have let him take the pistol to his head. She sat up abruptly. I tried to stop him, I told you that a million times. He wanted to do it, I couldn’t stop him. She brushed her hair back with her hand and screamed. The tears were coming and she was desperate to hold them back. Holding her hands over her ears she again opened her lips and a moan of agony escaped. Not knowing what else to do she allowed herself to scream, she screamed and screamed. They were laughing at her now. I thought you hated to scream? Don’t you feel better thought? Didn’t we tell you? &nbsp;They mocked her and laughed. <br />
"<br />
"ŒShe finally was able to close the gaping wound that was allowing the screams to leak away into the dark. To sew it shut she dug her teeth into her lip. The flesh cried strawberry wine that tasted like heartache. It dripped down onto her collarbone and soaked into her pale white shirt. His gold chain held tightly to her neck. She grabbed a hold of it. She knew it was thick and strong. The cold metal clutched in her hand she began to twist. The cool feel of it against her neck was almost the most pleasurable thing she had felt since she had felt his cool fingers push her hair back away from her neck. Tonight the chain was playing his part.<br />
" <br />
"ßShe twisted it tighter, the constriction around her throat made it almost impossible to even breathe. The rush felt good though. She had always thought she was particularly strong for not taking up drugs after the accident. Accident? They laughed. You know was no accident. You might as well just tighten that chain forever, you killed him. Another tear rolled down her cheek and she was finally sick of them. I didn’t kill him. I loved him. I just held his body when he was gone. I knew I couldn’t stop him so I told him I would take care of all that was left of the only thing I ever loved. The tears were coming faster and she tried to catch them in her hand so she wouldn’t slip away. All she was made of was tears anymore. <br />
"<br />
"^The hours on the clock ticked away slowly. She stared on into the night. They were awake and moved about her head. Going through her thoughts like tearing through an old file cabinet. Finding the painful ones and reading them aloud to her over and over again. She wondered how much more of this she could stand. Finally she reached her arm over to the bottle that contained about fifteen sleeping pills. With a quick gulp of water she downed the bottle and a smile of accomplishment came over her. She would surly sleep now. Grinning to herself she told them quietly, now you will have to be silent.<br />
"<br />
"©The sun began to rise and paint the sky in color. Leeann had not moved all night. One arm thrown precariously over the side of the bed. Her eyes began to open. She jumped with fright. This can't be true. Her heart raced with excitement. Its him, he's here she screamed. It must be true she thought. How can it not be when he is standing over me? He smiled, she melted. She was so ecstatic she had to tell her parents. <br />
"`Leaping and bounding from her bed she ran as fast as she could to her parents’ room.<br />
"<br />
"¬"Get up, get up now! He is here. He is in my room come and see him for yourself. I'm telling you I didn't kill him," she screeched in their ears. Drowsily her parents got to her feet and followed Leeann to her room. As the walked they noticed the spring in Leeann's step, the way she was acting made them wonder if she could possibly think he was really there. Rolling their eyes they continued to follow her to her room.<br />
"uThe anticipation was mounting for Leeann and she knew the moment she could prove that he was there, was the moment they would know she was not a murder. She loved him so much. The feel of the cold brass of her doorknob in her fingers was invigorating and she felt her moment near. She swung the door open and bounded into the room. She could smell him, hear him, and practically taste him. He was no where in sight. She heard her parents sigh behind her and then whisper to each other. No matter how hard she tried to stop them the tears poured over her cheeks. Then she heard their laughter. The torment it never stopped.<br />
"<br />
"=Looking at one another her parents just sighed. Her mother leaned over and whispered, "Maybe its about time for her to get some help from a professional. On an all the time basis." Her dad sighed. He didn't want her to have to leave, but it was tearing him apart to see her so tormented. He nodded at his wife.<br />
"<br />
"™That day as the clock ticked noon Leeann and her parents pulled up in front of Hollow Hills Institution. Her eyes widened. She heard the fear in their voices for the first time ever. She dragged her feet as she walked up the steps and down the eerie hallway. The walls were closing in on her and she already hated this place. Waiting at the end of the hallway was a woman. She was one of the most beautiful people Leeann had even seen. She was dressed all in white except for her black leggings, which had a run in them all the way up past where the skirt covered. Her blouse was cut a little to low and her black bra showed slightly when she moved. As Leeann approached, the woman she held her hand out and smiled warmly. Leeann attempted to smile, but it came out so half heartedly it ended up being less inviting then the scowl she had on before. The woman just took her hand and led her to a room in the back. <br />
"<br />
""Dr. Franst should be with you soon," before she left Leeann to herself she squeezed her hand softly and her eyes promised it would be ok. So Leeann sat in the dark and waited for a doctor she didn't know, to come and tell her all about the things that were wrong with her. <br />
"<br />
"A dark figure appeared in the doorway and her heart began to race. The voices were begging her to get out of this place. They were scared, and for a moment she felt like she had control of them. He looked at her with the darkest brown eyes she had ever seen. They were blacker than the night sky and not a star to see. She laid back on his bench. They were the most silent she had ever seen them. They weren't yelling at her or telling her to scream. It was almost as though they didn't want to be taken from her, although they seemed to hate her. She thought on this while Dr. Franst moved about the room. He pulled his chair up, got together his clipboard. She felt like she was being observed. She hated it and almost immediately a strong hate for the doctor grew. <br />
"<br />
""So, why is it that you are so sure the boy you killed was in your room the other night," Dr. Franst asked bluntly.<br />
" "I didn't kill him."<br />
"%"Ok, what happened then?"<br />
"k"Plain and simple, he wanted to die, he put that pistol to his head and I cleaned up the mess."<br />
"6"You know that is hard to believe, right?"<br />
"ñ"Yea, but I don't care. I know I didn't do it and that is all that matters. I loved him. I did then. I do now. Nothing will ever change that. He knew that I loved him and so I can live with myself as long as he knows that I love him."<br />
"L“How can you know for sure if he knew or not? Did you tell him?”<br />
"“He knew trust me.”<br />
"I“Leeann, so tell me about this past year since the accident.”<br />
"¯“Well most things considered everyone thought I was doing rather well. I went on like nothing had happened. I smiled, and I pretended to be happy. You know the norm...”<br />
"M“That doesn’t have to be the normal you know,” the doctor cut in.<br />
"9“Well ok it was always normal for me. Anyway, I went on about life. Most people didn’t talk to me much anymore because of what happened. To be honest I didn’t really care to much, at first. It took a very long time for the rumors to get to me just because I had no friends. So when it did, it hit me hard.”<br />
"K“What rumors are you talking about?” Dr. Franst asked politely.<br />
"“The ones saying that I had killed him,” she replied bluntly. “I didn’t know how to deal with it. I started to believe the rumors, I wondered if maybe I had killed him. I got very very lonely and that is when they came to join me. Misery loves company you know?”<br />
"G“Wait a moment,” he said slightly confused, “who are they?”<br />
"“They are the only ones who would talk to me; they kept me company when I just couldn’t stand it anymore. They were so loving and compassionate to me at first. Then their true colors began to show. They didn’t love me; they loved to hear my piercing screams echo in the night.”<br />
"4“So why did you let them stay?” he asked<br />
"Ï“Because they knew I was alive, and they knew I didn’t kill him. They thought it was funny to tell me I did, but they know as well as I do that I would not have killed him,” she replied in a monotone.<br />
"Í“How long does this stupid therapy thing go on for?” She asked glancing at the clock impatiently. Yes, yes we want to go home, they told her. Shut up I don’t care what you want, she snapped at them.<br />
"<br />
"/Dr. Franst wasn’t quite sure what to make of her. He couldn’t tell if she was lying to him or she truly believed the things she was telling him. She had obviously suffered a lot, but what her condition bad enough that she might have killed him. Her parents had brought her to him to get a diagnosis for court. Her trial was in three days. They wanted to plead her insane to get off the charges. She may never get better if she went to jail. He decided he could testify in court for this girl. He wanted to keep seeing her; he wanted her to get better. <br />
"<br />
"‰Leeann look around at the egg shell white walls. They were just as thin. She could hear people screaming everywhere. I don’t belong here. No, no you don’t, we should get out of here. She ignored them. They only want to make you hurt more she told herself, maybe I do belong here. Am I really insane? She laid down and went to sleep. It was easy unlike normal. She began to feel at home.<br />
"<br />
"„There she stood. It was judgment day. She stood in from of a jury of people she didn’t know. They were her either to condemn her or save her. She prayed for a savior. That is all she could ask for. They filed back in from the room when they made their verdict. Everyone looked up. The tension was so thick Leeann couldn’t even breathe. She felt a tear roll down her cheek. How could she win? If she was determined guilty then she would surely be in prison for a long time, and then everyone would be sure of a lie. But in her case was it any better to be innocent and have everyone think she was crazy? What is worse, prison or hospital?<br />
" <br />
"\“Have you reached a verdict?” the judge said slicing right through the silence. <br />
"W“We have your honor. We find the Defendant…” Leeann drew in a sharp breath.<br />
"Ì“Innocent.” The lead juror smiled at Leeann. But Leeann just starred off. Innocent? Innocent, are you kidding me? You did it. They wouldn’t stop. Jumping up in the middle of the room she screamed. <br />
"<br />
"#“Leave me alone! I hate you! I was never lonely enough for you, miserable enough, desperate enough. I didn’t kill him, I have my proof now. I don’t need you anymore.” And with that she walked out of the court room. Down the street and to her house where she sat down and fell asleep. <br />
"éLeeann’s parents were slightly worried; she had been sleeping for about three days and wasn’t eating. They thought about taking her back to Hollow Hills. They knew though she wouldn’t want to go back. They decided to wake her.<br />
"<br />
"_Leeann stirred with the feel of a hand on her arm. She opened her eyes, this time she felt the most relief she had ever felt. When she felt that hand on her arm she didn’t think it was him. She didn’t hear herself screaming that is was. She knew it was her parents and it was comforting. Opening her eyes she looked up at them, smiled and said,<br />
"|“It’s finally really going to be ok. It is really going to be ok this time.” With that she feel back onto the couch. <br />
"<br />
"Õ“They will all know now, the whole world will know that I loved him. That is all that I ever wanted. And they, they are finally quiet. How can the argue with the whole world?” She laid back and slept again.<br />
"ØHer parents just smiled. They knew she was telling the truth. It was so hard for them to believe before. But the way she told them it would be ok. They knew it would. There is almost no wound that time doesn’t heal.
"End of Poem
